SIMPLE: manger
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: manger
<hw>man"ger</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>mangeoire</ets>, fr. <ets>manger</ets> to eat, fr. L.
<ets>manducare</ets>, fr. <ets>mandere</ets> to chew. Cf.
<er>Mandible</er>, <er>Manducate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A trough
or open box in which fodder is placed for horses or cattle to
eat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And she brought forth her firstborn son, and wrapped him in
swaddling clothes, and laid him in a <qex>manger</qex>; because there
was no room for them in the inn.</q> <rj><qau>Luke 2: 7</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The fore part of the deck, having
a bulkhead athwart ships high enough to prevent water which enters the
hawse holes from running over it.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mangey</ent>⟦br⟧
